{
    "id": "plurals-grammar",
    "title": "Unit 8 Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass: Plural Nouns and Articles",
    "curriculum_id": "unit-8-grammar",
    "voices": {
        "en": "en-AU-WilliamMultilingualNeural",
        "gr": "el-GR-AthinaNeural",
        "gr_en": "en-US-AvaMultilingualNeural"
    },
    "script": [
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Welcome... to the Learn Greek Grammar Masterclass for Unit 8: Plural Nouns and Articles. So far... we've lived in a world of 'ones'. One car... one friend... one book. But life is full of groups. In English... we just add 'S'. In Greek... we change the article... and we change the ending... but we do it with systematic rules. I'm William... and here with me is Athina. Athina... where do we start with the many?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γεια σας!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "We start with the Article. This is your first signal that we are talking about more than one. Let's look at Masculine first."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ο φίλος..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "the friend (singular)... becomes..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Οι φίλοι."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Wait..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Οι;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "That's the same sound as the feminine article"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "η"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "from Unit 2. Is that right?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Phonetically... yes! Both are 'ee'. But in writing... the masculine plural is"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Οι."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Okay... so 'ee' for the article... and 'ee' for the noun ending. It's another rhyme! What about Feminine?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Η φίλη..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "singular... becomes..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Οι φίλες."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So the article for BOTH masculine and feminine plural is"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Οι;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Yes! Both are"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Οι."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "This makes the plural article very easy to remember. Just use"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "οι"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "for everyone except the neuters."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Ah... the neuters. They always have their own path."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Το παιδί..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "becomes..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τα παιδιά."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Το"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "becomes"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τα..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "and the ending changes. It sounds very different. What about the other types of endings? Like"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "πατέρας"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "or"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "θάλασσα;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "Masculine nouns ending in"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ας"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "or"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ης"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "use the ending"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ες."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Ο πατέρας... Οι πατέρες. Ο μαθητής... Οι μαθητές."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "And Feminine nouns?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Η θάλασσα... Οι θάλασσες. Η αγάπη... Οι αγάπες."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "So"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-ες"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "is the king of plural endings for many nouns. And finally... the Neuter nouns that end in"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "-μα;"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Το μάθημα... Τα μαθήματα."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "We add a"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "τα"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "at the end. It sounds like a drumbeat!"
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Wait... I noticed something. Does the accent mark... the"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Τόνος..."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "ever move when we pluralize?"
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr_en",
            "text": "In regular nouns... no! It stays exactly where it was. If it was on the first syllable... it stays there."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Μάθημα... Μαθήματα."
        },
        {
            "voice": "en",
            "text": "Got it. This has been a great dive into the world of 'Groups'. You now know the plural articles and the four common plural endings. Practice with the pluralization worksheet and try turning your singular vocabulary into pairs. Excellent work... we'll see you in Unit 9: Genitive Case and Possession."
        },
        {
            "voice": "gr",
            "text": "Γεια σας!"
        }
    ]
}